{"word":"ἀρήγω","slug":"ἀρήγω","sections":[{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":"<el><b>ἀρήγω</b></el> <br/><b><a href='S:Etymology'>Etym.</a> </b>akin to <a href='S:ἀρκέω'><el>ἀρκέω</el></a>\n<p/><div class='li500'><b>I. </b><i>to help, aid, succour</i>, <a href='S:especially'>esp.</a> in battle, <a href='S:cum'>c.</a> <a href='S:dative'>dat.</a>, <b><a href='S:Iliad'>Il.</a></b>, <b><a href='S:Herodotus'>Hdt.</a></b><p/></div><div class='li750'><b>2. </b><a href='S:impersonal'>impers.</a>, <a href='S:cum'>c.</a> <a href='S:infinitive'>inf.</a>, like Lat, <i>juvat, it is good</i> or <i>fit</i>, <el>σιγᾶν ἀρήγει</el> <b><a href='S:Aeschylus'>Aesch.</a></b><p/></div><div class='li500'><b>II. </b><a href='S:cum'>c.</a> <a href='S:accusative'>acc.</a> rei, <i>to ward off, prevent</i>, <el>τι</el> <b><a href='S:Aeschylus'>Aesch.</a></b>; also, <el>ἀρ. τί τινι</el> <i>to ward off from</i> one, <b><a href='S:Euripides'>Eur.</a></b><p/></div>"}]}